## Parsing Structured Text with Recursion

Real-world text often has structure hidden inside it: key-value pairs separated by delimiters, CSV rows, simple tag-value formats. Parsing means turning that linear string into a structured list or association list that the rest of your program can route through.

Let's write a parser for a simple key-value format: `\"name:Alice,age:30,city:Portland\"`. We'll split on commas, then split each segment on colons, building an association list.

```scheme
;; Parse a key-value string like \"name:Alice,age:30,city:Portland\".
(define (parse-kv text)
  (define (split-on-char str ch)
    (define (split-helper chars acc word-acc)
      (cond
        ((null? chars)
         (reverse (cons (list->string (reverse word-acc)) acc)))
        ((char=? (car chars) ch)
         (split-helper (cdr chars)
                       (cons (list->string (reverse word-acc)) acc)
                       '()))
        (else
         (split-helper (cdr chars) acc (cons (car chars) word-acc)))))
    (split-helper (string->list str) '() '()))
  
  (define (parse-pair pair-str)
    (let ((parts (split-on-char pair-str #\\:)))
      (if (= (length parts) 2)
          (cons (string->symbol (car parts)) (cadr parts))
          #f)))
  
  (let ((pairs (split-on-char text #\\,)))
    (let ((parsed (map parse-pair pairs)))
      (if (member #f parsed)
          (escalate 'malformed-kv text)
          parsed))))

(parse-kv \"name:Alice,age:30,city:Portland\")
;; => ((name . \"Alice\") (age . \"30\") (city . \"Portland\"))
```

We split on commas, then split each piece on colons. If any piece lacks a colon, `parse-pair` returns `#f`, and we escalate. **ESCAPE** is validation: we check the structure before returning it as valid.

Now let's extend this: parse the key-value string, then normalize all the *values* (in case they have extra whitespace), and finally look up a specific key.

```scheme
;; Parse key-value text, normalize all values, and look up a key.
(define (parse-normalize-lookup text key)
  (define (split-on-char str ch)
    (define (split-helper chars acc word-acc)
      (cond
        ((null? chars)
         (reverse (cons (list->string (reverse word-acc)) acc)))
        ((char=? (car chars) ch)
         (split-helper (cdr chars)
                       (cons (list->string (reverse word-acc)) acc)
                       '()))
        (else
         (split-helper (cdr chars) acc (cons (car chars) word-acc)))))
    (split-helper (string->list str) '() '()))
  
  (define (parse-pair pair-str)
    (let ((parts (split-on-char pair-str #\\:)))
      (if (= (length parts) 2)
          (cons (string->symbol (car parts)) (cadr parts))
          #f)))
  
  (let ((pairs (split-on-char text #\\,)))
    (let ((parsed (map parse-pair pairs)))
      (if (member #f parsed)
          (escalate 'malformed-kv text)
          (let ((normalized (map (lambda (pair)
                                   (let ((k (car pair))
                                         (v (cdr pair)))
                                     (let ((nv (text/normalize v)))
                                       (if (equal? nv 'nan)
                                           (cons k v)
                                           (cons k nv)))))
                                 parsed)))
            (let ((entry (assoc key normalized)))
              (if entry
                  (cdr entry)
                  (escalate 'key-not-found (list (cons 'key key)
                                                 (cons 'available (map car normalized)))))))))))

(parse-normalize-lookup \"name:  Alice  ,age: 30 ,city: Portland \" 'city)
;; => \"portland\"
```

We parsed, normalized each value, then looked up `city`—and got `\"portland\"` (normalized to lowercase, whitespace stripped). If we'd looked up `'country`, we'd get `(escalate key-not-found ...)`. **FORWARD** is layered composition: parse → normalize → lookup, with each stage building on the last.

---

## Templating: From Data to Formatted Text

Parsing goes one way (text → data); templating goes the other (data → text). Given a template string with placeholders and an association list of values, we want to replace each placeholder with its corresponding value.

Let's write a simple templater: placeholders are `{{key}}`, and we substitute from an alist.

```scheme
;; Simple template engine: replace {{key}} with values from an alist.
(define (template tmpl alist)
  (define (find-placeholder str start)
    ;; Find the next {{ in the string starting at index start.
    ;; Returns (start-idx . end-idx) or #f if not found.
    (define (search idx)
      (cond
        ((>= idx (- (string-length str) 1)) #f)
        ((and (char=? (string-ref str idx) #\\{)
              (char=? (string-ref str (+ idx 1)) #\\{))
         (let ((end (find-close str (+ idx 2))))
           (if end
               (cons idx end)
               #f)))
        (else (search (+ idx 1)))))
    (search start))
  
  (define (find-close str start)
    ;; Find the next }} starting at index start.
    (define (search idx)
      (cond
        ((>= idx (- (string-length str) 1)) #f)
        ((and (char=? (string-ref str idx) #\\})
              (char=? (string-ref str (+ idx 1)) #\\}))
         (+ idx 2))
        (else (search (+ idx 1)))))
    (search start))
  
  (define (substitute str)
    (let ((match (find-placeholder str 0)))
      (if match
          (let ((start (car match))
                (end (cdr match)))
            (let ((key-str (substring str (+ start 2) (- end 2))))
              (let ((key (string->symbol key-str)))
                (let ((entry (assoc key alist)))
                  (if entry
                      (let ((value (cdr entry)))
                        (string-append
                          (substring str 0 start)
                          value
                          (substitute (substring str end (string-length str)))))
                      (escalate 'key-not-found (list (cons 'key key)
                                                     (cons 'template tmpl))))))))
          str)))
  
  (substitute tmpl))

(template \"Hello, {{name}}! You have {{count}} new messages.\"
          '((name . \"Alice\") (count . \"3\")))
;; => \"Hello, Alice! You have 3 new messages.\"
```

We scan for `{{`, extract the key name, look it up in the alist, and substitute the value. If a key is missing, we escalate. **ESCAPE** is clean: no silent placeholder passthrough, no fake substitution.

Now let's combine parsing and templating into a single pipeline: parse a key-value config string, then use those values to fill a template.

```scheme
;; Parse a config string, then use it to fill a template.
(define (config-template config-str tmpl-str)
  (define (split-on-char str ch)
    (define (split-helper chars acc word-acc)
      (cond
        ((null? chars)
         (reverse (cons (list->string (reverse word-acc)) acc)))
        ((char=? (car chars) ch)
         (split-helper (cdr chars)
                       (cons (list->string (reverse word-acc)) acc)
                       '()))
        (else
         (split-helper (cdr chars) acc (cons (car chars) word-acc)))))
    (split-helper (string->list str) '() '()))
  
  (define (parse-pair pair-str)
    (let ((parts (split-on-char pair-str #\\:)))
      (if (= (length parts) 2)
          (cons (string->symbol (car parts)) (cadr parts))
          #f)))
  
  (define (parse-kv text)
    (let ((pairs (split-on-char text #\\,)))
      (let ((parsed (map parse-pair pairs)))
        (if (member #f parsed)
            (escalate 'malformed-kv text)
            parsed))))
  
  (define (find-placeholder str start)
    (define (search idx)
      (cond
        ((>= idx (- (string-length str) 1)) #f)
        ((and (char=? (string-ref str idx) #\\{)
              (char=? (string-ref str (+ idx 1)) #\\{))
         (let ((end (find-close str (+ idx 2))))
           (if end
               (cons idx end)
               #f)))
        (else (search (+ idx 1)))))
    (search start))
  
  (define (find-close str start)
    (define (search idx)
      (cond
        ((>= idx (- (string-length str) 1)) #f)
        ((and (char=? (string-ref str idx) #\\})
              (char=? (string-ref str (+ idx 1)) #\\}))
         (+ idx 2))
        (else (search (+ idx 1)))))
    (search start))
  
  (define (template tmpl alist)
    (define (substitute str)
      (let ((match (find-placeholder str 0)))
        (if match
            (let ((start (car match))
                  (end (cdr match)))
              (let ((key-str (substring str (+ start 2) (- end 2))))
                (let ((key (string->symbol key-str)))
                  (let ((entry (assoc key alist)))
                    (if entry
                        (let ((value (cdr entry)))
                          (string-append
                            (substring str 0 start)
                            value
                            (substitute (substring str end (string-length str)))))
                        (escalate 'key-not-found (list (cons 'key key)
                                                       (cons 'template tmpl))))))))
            str)))
    (substitute tmpl))
  
  (let ((config (parse-kv config-str)))
    (if (and (pair? config) (equal? (car config) 'escalate))
        config
        (template tmpl-str config))))

(config-template \"customer:Alice,item:Scarf,price:45\"
                 \"Dear {{customer}}, your {{item}} is ready. Total: ${{price}}.\")
;; => \"Dear Alice, your Scarf is ready. Total: $45.\"
```

Parse → template. If parsing fails, we return the escalation immediately; if templating fails (missing key), we return that escalation. **FORWARD** is sequential routing: the output of parse is the input to template, and we never proceed if a stage fails.

