## Multi-Stage Text Pipeline: Parse, Transform, Format

Let's take everything we've learned and build a genuinely hard program: a multi-stage pipeline that (1) parses a CSV-like string into rows, (2) transforms each row by normalizing text fields and computing a derived field, (3) formats the result as a human-readable summary using a template.

The CSV format: `\"name,role,years\\nAlice,Engineer,5\\nBob,Designer,3\"`. We'll parse it, compute a \"seniority\" label based on years, normalize the role, and emit a formatted report.

```scheme
;; Parse CSV rows, transform with normalization and derived fields, format output.
(define (csv-transform-report csv-str)
  (define (split-on-char str ch)
    (define (split-helper chars acc word-acc)
      (cond
        ((null? chars)
         (reverse (cons (list->string (reverse word-acc)) acc)))
        ((char=? (car chars) ch)
         (split-helper (cdr chars)
                       (cons (list->string (reverse word-acc)) acc)
                       '()))
        (else
         (split-helper (cdr chars) acc (cons (car chars) word-acc)))))
    (split-helper (string->list str) '() '()))
  
  ;; Step 1: Parse CSV into list of rows (each row is a list of fields).
  (define (parse-csv text)
    (let ((lines (split-on-char text #\\newline)))
      (if (null? lines)
          (escalate 'empty-csv text)
          (let ((header (split-on-char (car lines) #\\,)))
            (let ((rows (map (lambda (line) (split-on-char line #\\,)) (cdr lines))))
              (if (any? (lambda (row) (not (= (length row) (length header)))) rows)
                  (escalate 'uneven-columns text)
                  (cons header rows)))))))
  
  (define (any? pred lst)
    (and (not (null? lst))
         (or (pred (car lst))
             (any? pred (cdr lst)))))
  
  ;; Step 2: Transform each row—normalize role, compute seniority.
  (define (transform-rows header rows)
    (define name-idx (list-index \"name\" header))
    (define role-idx (list-index \"role\" header))
    (define years-idx (list-index \"years\" header))
    
    (define (list-index item lst)
      (define (search idx remaining)
        (cond
          ((null? remaining) #f)
          ((equal? (car remaining) item) idx)
          (else (search (+ idx 1) (cdr remaining)))))
      (search 0 lst))
    
    (if (or (not name-idx) (not role-idx) (not years-idx))
        (escalate 'missing-columns (list (cons 'header header)
                                         (cons 'expected '(\"name\" \"role\" \"years\"))))
        (map (lambda (row)
               (let ((name (list-ref row name-idx))
                     (role (list-ref row role-idx))
                     (years-str (list-ref row years-idx)))
                 (let ((years (string->number years-str)))
                   (if (not years)
                       (escalate 'invalid-years years-str)
                       (let ((norm-role (text/normalize role)))
                         (if (equal? norm-role 'nan)
                             (escalate 'normalize-failed role)
                             (let ((seniority (cond
                                                ((< years 2) \"junior\")
                                                ((< years 5) \"mid-level\")
                                                (else \"senior\"))))
                               (list (cons 'name name)
                                     (cons 'role norm-role)
                                     (cons 'years years)
                                     (cons 'seniority seniority)))))))))
             rows)))
  
  ;; Step 3: Format each transformed row as a summary line.
  (define (format-report rows)
    (define (format-one row)
      (let ((name (cdr (assoc 'name row)))
            (role (cdr (assoc 'role row)))
            (years (cdr (assoc 'years row)))
            (seniority (cdr (assoc 'seniority row))))
        (string-append name \" (\" seniority \" \" role \", \" (number->string years) \" years)\")))
    (map format-one rows))
  
  ;; Pipeline: parse → transform → format.
  (let ((parsed (parse-csv csv-str)))
    (if (and (pair? parsed) (equal? (car parsed) 'escalate))
        parsed
        (let ((header (car parsed))
              (rows (cdr parsed)))
          (let ((transformed (transform-rows header rows)))
            (if (and (pair? transformed) (equal? (car transformed) 'escalate))
                transformed
                (format-report transformed)))))))

(csv-transform-report \"name,role,years\\nAlice,Engineer,5\\nBob,Designer,3\")
;; => (\"Alice (senior engineer, 5 years)\" \"Bob (mid-level designer, 3 years)\")
```

Three stages: parse CSV → transform (normalize role, derive seniority) → format. Each stage can fail, and we check at every boundary. If Bob's years were `\"three\"` instead of `\"3\"`, we'd escalate `(invalid-years \"three\")`. **ESCAPE** is thorough: every verb call, every parse step, every lookup is guarded.

Now let's extend this: after transformation, filter rows by seniority, then format only the filtered subset.

```scheme
;; Parse, transform, filter by seniority, then format.
(define (csv-filter-report csv-str seniority-filter)
  (define (split-on-char str ch)
    (define (split-helper chars acc word-acc)
      (cond
        ((null? chars)
         (reverse (cons (list->string (reverse word-acc)) acc)))
        ((char=? (car chars) ch)
         (split-helper (cdr chars)
                       (cons (list->string (reverse word-acc)) acc)
                       '()))
        (else
         (split-helper (cdr chars) acc (cons (car chars) word-acc)))))
    (split-helper (string->list str) '() '()))
  
  (define (parse-csv text)
    (let ((lines (split-on-char text #\\newline)))
      (if (null? lines)
          (escalate 'empty-csv text)
          (let ((header (split-on-char (car lines) #\\,)))
            (let ((rows (map (lambda (line) (split-on-char line #\\,)) (cdr lines))))
              (if (any? (lambda (row) (not (= (length row) (length header)))) rows)
                  (escalate 'uneven-columns text)
                  (cons header rows)))))))
  
  (define (any? pred lst)
    (and (not (null? lst))
         (or (pred (car lst))
             (any? pred (cdr lst)))))
  
  (define (transform-rows header rows)
    (define name-idx (list-index \"name\" header))
    (define role-idx (list-index \"role\" header))
    (define years-idx (list-index \"years\" header))
    
    (define (list-index item lst)
      (define (search idx remaining)
        (cond
          ((null? remaining) #f)
          ((equal? (car remaining) item) idx)
          (else (search (+ idx 1) (cdr remaining)))))
      (search 0 lst))
    
    (if (or (not name-idx) (not role-idx) (not years-idx))
        (escalate 'missing-columns (list (cons 'header header)
                                         (cons 'expected '(\"name\" \"role\" \"years\"))))
        (map (lambda (row)
               (let ((name (list-ref row name-idx))
                     (role (list-ref row role-idx))
                     (years-str (list-ref row years-idx)))
                 (let ((years (string->number years-str)))
                   (if (not years)
                       (escalate 'invalid-years years-str)
                       (let ((norm-role (text/normalize role)))
                         (if (equal? norm-role 'nan)
                             (escalate 'normalize-failed role)
                             (let ((seniority (cond
                                                ((< years 2) \"junior\")
                                                ((< years 5) \"mid-level\")
                                                (else \"senior\"))))
                               (list (cons 'name name)
                                     (cons 'role norm-role)
                                     (cons 'years years)
                                     (cons 'seniority seniority)))))))))
             rows)))
  
  (define (format-report rows)
    (define (format-one row)
      (let ((name (cdr (assoc 'name row)))
            (role (cdr (assoc 'role row)))
            (years (cdr (assoc 'years row)))
            (seniority (cdr (assoc 'seniority row))))
        (string-append name \" (\" seniority \" \" role \", \" (number->string years) \" years)\")))
    (map format-one rows))
  
  (let ((parsed (parse-csv csv-str)))
    (if (and (pair? parsed) (equal? (car parsed) 'escalate))
        parsed
        (let ((header (car parsed))
              (rows (cdr parsed)))
          (let ((transformed (transform-rows header rows)))
            (if (and (pair? transformed) (equal? (car transformed) 'escalate))
                transformed
                (let ((filtered (filter (lambda (row)
                                          (equal? (cdr (assoc 'seniority row))
                                                  seniority-filter))
                                        transformed)))
                  (if (null? filtered)
                      (escalate 'no-matches seniority-filter)
                      (format-report filtered)))))))))

(csv-filter-report \"name,role,years\\nAlice,Engineer,5\\nBob,Designer,3\\nCarol,Manager,1\"
                   \"senior\")
;; => (\"Alice (senior engineer, 5 years)\")
```

Only Alice matches the `\"senior\"` filter. If we'd filtered on `\"executive\"`, we'd get `(escalate no-matches \"executive\")`. **FORWARD** is selective: we route only the data that passes the filter to the next stage.

---

## Recursive Text Transformation: Nested Placeholder Expansion

Let's tackle a harder templating problem: templates can reference other templates by name, and we need to expand them recursively. For example, a greeting template might include `{{salutation}}`, which itself expands to `\"Hello, {{name}}\"`.

We'll maintain a dictionary of named templates and recursively expand until no placeholders remain (or we detect a cycle).

```scheme
;; Recursive template expansion with cycle detection.
(define (recursive-template root-template values templates max-depth)
  (define (find-placeholder str start)
    (define (search idx)
      (cond
        ((>= idx (- (string-length str) 1)) #f)
        ((and (char=? (string-ref str idx) #\\{)
              (char=? (string-ref str (+ idx 1)) #\\{))
         (let ((end (find-close str (+ idx 2))))
           (if end
               (cons idx end)
               #f)))
        (else (search (+ idx 1)))))
    (search start))
  
  (define (find-close str start)
    (define (search idx)
      (cond
        ((>= idx (- (string-length str) 1)) #f)
        ((and (char=? (string-ref str idx) #\\})
              (char=? (string-ref str (+ idx 1)) #\\}))
         (+ idx 2))
        (else (search (+ idx 1)))))
    (search start))
  
  (define (expand str depth)
    (if (> depth max-depth)
        (escalate 'max-depth-exceeded max-depth)
        (let ((match (find-placeholder str 0)))
          (if match
              (let ((start (car match))
                    (end (cdr match)))
                (let ((key-str (substring str (+ start 2) (- end 2))))
                  (let ((key (string->symbol key-str)))
                    (let ((value-entry (assoc key values))
                          (template-entry (assoc key templates)))
                      (cond
                        (value-entry
                         (let ((value (cdr value-entry)))
                           (expand (string-append
                                     (substring str 0 start)
                                     value
                                     (substring str end (string-length str)))
                                   depth)))
                        (template-entry
                         (let ((tmpl (cdr template-entry)))
                           (let ((expanded-tmpl (expand tmpl (+ depth 1))))
                             (if (and (pair? expanded-tmpl) (equal? (car expanded-tmpl) 'escalate))
                                 expanded-tmpl
                                 (expand (string-append
                                           (substring str 0 start)
                                           expanded-tmpl
                                           (substring str end (string-length str)))
                                         depth)))))
                        (else
                         (escalate 'key-not-found key)))))))
              str))))
  
  (expand root-template 0))

(recursive-template \"{{greeting}}, how can I help you today?\"
                    '((name . \"Alice\"))
                    '((greeting . \"Hello, {{name}}\"))
                    10)
;; => \"Hello, Alice, how can I help you today?\"
```

The root template contains `{{greeting}}`, which expands to `\"Hello, {{name}}\"`, which then expands to `\"Hello, Alice\"`. If we'd hit a cycle (e.g., `greeting` → `salutation` → `greeting`), we'd exceed `max-depth` and escalate. **ESCAPE** is depth-limited: we don't allow infinite recursion.

Now let's add a second level of nesting: `greeting` → `salutation` → `name`.

```scheme
;; Three-level nested template expansion.
(define (three-level-template root values templates max-depth)
  (define (find-placeholder str start)
    (define (search idx)
      (cond
        ((>= idx (- (string-length str) 1)) #f)
        ((and (char=? (string-ref str idx) #\\{)
              (char=? (string-ref str (+ idx 1)) #\\{))
         (let ((end (find-close str (+ idx 2))))
           (if end
               (cons idx end)
               #f)))
        (else (search (+ idx 1)))))
    (search start))
  
  (define (find-close str start)
    (define (search idx)
      (cond
        ((>= idx (- (string-length str) 1)) #f)
        ((and (char=? (string-ref str idx) #\\})
              (char=? (string-ref str (+ idx 1)) #\\}))
         (+ idx 2))
        (else (search (+ idx 1)))))
    (search start))
  
  (define (expand str depth)
    (if (> depth max-depth)
        (escalate 'max-depth-exceeded max-depth)
        (let ((match (find-placeholder str 0)))
          (if match
              (let ((start (car match))
                    (end (cdr match)))
                (let ((key-str (substring str (+ start 2) (- end 2))))
                  (let ((key (string->symbol key-str)))
                    (let ((value-entry (assoc key values))
                          (template-entry (assoc key templates)))
                      (cond
                        (value-entry
                         (let ((value (cdr value-entry)))
                           (expand (string-append
                                     (substring str 0 start)
                                     value
                                     (substring str end (string-length str)))
                                   depth)))
                        (template-entry
                         (let ((tmpl (cdr template-entry)))
                           (let ((expanded-tmpl (expand tmpl (+ depth 1))))
                             (if (and (pair? expanded-tmpl) (equal? (car expanded-tmpl) 'escalate))
                                 expanded-tmpl
                                 (expand (string-append
                                           (substring str 0 start)
                                           expanded-tmpl
                                           (substring str end (string-length str)))
                                         depth)))))
                        (else
                         (escalate 'key-not-found key)))))))
              str))))
  
  (expand root 0))

(three-level-template \"{{greeting}}\"
                      '((name . \"Bob\") (title . \"Dr.\"))
                      '((greeting . \"{{salutation}}, how are you?\")
                        (salutation . \"{{title}} {{name}}\"))
                      10)
;; => \"Dr. Bob, how are you?\"
```

Root → `greeting` → `salutation` → `title` and `name`. Three levels of expansion. If we'd set `max-depth` to 2, we'd escalate before reaching `name`. **BACK** is parameterization: we don't hardcode the depth limit—we pass it in, making the function reusable for different risk tolerances.

---

## Composing Text Verbs: Normalize, Slug, Distance, and Format

Let's write a program that orchestrates all the text verbs we have: given a list of product titles, normalize each, generate slugs, compute pairwise distances between slugs (to detect near-duplicates), and format a report of any pairs within a threshold.

This is a genuinely hard program: it uses `text/normalize`, `system/slugify`, `text/distance`, nested loops, and formatting—all with honest failure handling.

```scheme
;; Find near-duplicate product titles by slug distance.
(define (find-near-duplicates titles threshold)
  (define (normalize-and-slug title)
    (let ((norm (text/normalize title)))
      (if (equal? norm 'nan)
          (escalate 'normalize-failed title)
          (let ((slug (system/slugify norm)))
            (if (equal? slug 'nan)
                (escalate 'slugify-failed norm)
                (list (cons 'title title)
                      (cons 'slug slug)))))))
  
  (define (all-pairs lst)
    (define (pairs-with-first first rest)
      (if (null? rest)
          '()
          (cons (cons first (car rest))
                (pairs-with-first first (cdr rest)))))
    (if (null? lst)
        '()
        (append (pairs-with-first (car lst) (cdr lst))
                (all-pairs (cdr lst)))))
  
  (define (compute-distance pair)
    (let ((slug-a (cdr (assoc 'slug (car pair))))
          (slug-b (cdr (assoc 'slug (cdr pair)))))
      (let ((dist (text/distance slug-a slug-b)))
        (if (equal? dist 'nan)
            (escalate 'distance-failed (list slug-a slug-b))
            (list (cons 'title-a (cdr (assoc 'title (car pair))))
                  (cons 'title-b (cdr (assoc 'title (cdr pair))))
                  (cons 'slug-a slug-a)
                  (cons 'slug-b slug-b)
                  (cons 'distance dist))))))
  
  (let ((processed (map normalize-and-slug titles)))
    (if (any? (lambda (x) (and (pair? x) (equal? (car x) 'escalate))) processed)
        (car (filter (lambda (x) (and (pair? x) (equal? (car x) 'escalate))) processed))
        (let ((pairs (all-pairs processed)))
          (if (null? pairs)
              '()
              (let ((distances (map compute-distance pairs)))
                (if (any? (lambda (x) (and (pair? x) (equal? (car x) 'escalate))) distances)
                    (car (filter (lambda (x) (and (pair? x) (equal? (car x) 'escalate))) distances))
                    (let ((near (filter (lambda (d) (<= (cdr (assoc 'distance d)) threshold))
                                        distances)))
                      near))))))))

(define (any? pred lst)
  (and (not (null? lst))
       (or (pred (car lst))
           (any? pred (cdr lst)))))

(find-near-duplicates '(\"Hand-Knit Wool Scarf\"
                        \"Handknit Wool Scarf\"
                        \"Machine-Knit Cotton Throw\")
                      2)
;; => (((title-a . \"Hand-Knit Wool Scarf\")
;;      (title-b . \"Handknit Wool Scarf\")
;;      (slug-a . \"hand-knit-wool-scarf\")
;;      (slug-b . \"handknit-wool-scarf\")
;;      (distance . 1)))
```

The first two titles have slugs one character apart—they're near-duplicates. The third is far enough away that it doesn't appear. This program composes five techniques: normalization, slugification, distance computation, pairwise comparison, and filtering. **FORWARD** is orchestration: each stage feeds the next, and we only proceed if all stages succeed.

---

## Full Pipeline: Fetch, Parse, Transform, Template, Validate

Let's build the hardest program in this chapter: a full data pipeline that (1) simulates fetching text data (we'll use a hardcoded string as if it came from `web/fetch`), (2) parses it as CSV, (3) transforms rows (normalize, derive fields), (4) filters by criteria, (5) templates each result into a message, (6) validates each message's word count and readability, and (7) returns the list of valid messages or the first escalation.

```scheme
;; Full pipeline: parse CSV, transform, filter, template, validate.
(define (full-text-pipeline csv-str min-years template-str min-words max-words max-grade)
  (define (split-on-char str ch)
    (define (split-helper chars acc word-acc)
      (cond
        ((null? chars)
         (reverse (cons (list->string (reverse word-acc)) acc)))
        ((char=? (car chars) ch)
         (split-helper (cdr chars)
                       (cons (list->string (reverse word-acc)) acc)
                       '()))
        (else
         (split-helper (cdr chars) acc (cons (car chars) word-acc)))))
    (split-helper (string->list str) '() '()))
  
  ;; Step 1: Parse CSV.
  (define (parse-csv text)
    (let ((lines (split-on-char text #\\newline)))
      (if (null? lines)
          (escalate 'empty-csv text)
          (let ((header (split-on-char (car lines) #\\,)))
            (let ((rows (map (lambda (line) (split-on-char line #\\,)) (cdr lines))))
              (if (any? (lambda (row) (not (= (length row) (length header)))) rows)
                  (escalate 'uneven-columns text)
                  (cons header rows)))))))
  
  (define (any? pred lst)
    (and (not (null? lst))
         (or (pred (car lst))
             (any? pred (cdr lst)))))
  
  ;; Step 2: Transform rows.
  (define (transform-rows header rows)
    (define name-idx (list-index \"name\" header))
    (define role-idx (list-index \"role\" header))
    (define years-idx (list-index \"years\" header))
    
    (define (list-index item lst)
      (define (search idx remaining)
        (cond
          ((null? remaining) #f)
          ((equal? (car remaining) item) idx)
          (else (search (+ idx 1) (cdr remaining)))))
      (search 0 lst))
    
    (if (or (not name-idx) (not role-idx) (not years-idx))
        (escalate 'missing-columns (list (cons 'header header)
                                         (cons 'expected '(\"name\" \"role\" \"years\"))))
        (map (lambda (row)
               (let ((name (list-ref row name-idx))
                     (role (list-ref row role-idx))
                     (years-str (list-ref row years-idx)))
                 (let ((years (string->number years-str)))
                   (if (not years)
                       (escalate 'invalid-years years-str)
                       (let ((norm-role (text/normalize role)))
                         (if (equal? norm-role 'nan)
                             (escalate 'normalize-failed role)
                             (list (cons 'name name)
                                   (cons 'role norm-role)
                                   (cons 'years years))))))))
             rows)))
  
  ;; Step 3: Filter by minimum years.
  (define (filter-by-years rows min-y)
    (filter (lambda (row)
              (>= (cdr (assoc 'years row)) min-y))
            rows))
  
  ;; Step 4: Template each row into a message.
  (define (template-rows rows tmpl)
    (define (find-placeholder str start)
      (define (search idx)
        (cond
          ((>= idx (- (string-length str) 1)) #f)
          ((and (char=? (string-ref str idx) #\\{)
                (char=? (string-ref str (+ idx 1)) #\\{))
           (let ((end (find-close str (+ idx 2))))
             (if end
                 (cons idx end)
                 #f)))
          (else (search (+ idx 1)))))
      (search start))
    
    (define (find-close str start)
      (define (search idx)
        (cond
          ((>= idx (- (string-length str) 1)) #f)
          ((and (char=? (string-ref str idx) #\\})
                (char=? (string-ref str (+ idx 1)) #\\}))
           (+ idx 2))
          (else (search (+ idx 1)))))
      (search start))
    
    (define (template-one alist)
      (define (substitute str)
        (let ((match (find-placeholder str 0)))
          (if match
              (let ((start (car match))
                    (end (cdr match)))
                (let ((key-str (substring str (+ start 2) (- end 2))))
                  (let ((key (string->symbol key-str)))
                    (let ((entry (assoc key alist)))
                      (if entry
                          (let ((value (cond
                                         ((string? (cdr entry)) (cdr entry))
                                         ((number? (cdr entry)) (number->string (cdr entry)))
                                         (else (symbol->string (cdr entry))))))
                            (substitute (string-append
                                          (substring str 0 start)
                                          value
                                          (substring str end (string-length str)))))
                          (escalate 'key-not-found (list (cons 'key key)
                                                         (cons 'template tmpl))))))))
              str)))
      (substitute tmpl))
    
    (map template-one rows))
  
  ;; Step 5: Validate each message.
  (define (validate-messages messages)
    (define (validate-one msg)
      (let ((wc (text/word-count msg)))
        (if (equal? wc 'nan)
            (escalate 'word-count-failed msg)
            (let ((grade (text/flesch-kincaid msg)))
              (if (equal? grade 'nan)
                  (escalate 'readability-failed msg)
                  (cond
                    ((< wc min-words)
                     (escalate 'too-short (list (cons 'message msg)
                                                (cons 'words wc)
                                                (cons 'min min-words))))
                    ((> wc max-words)
                     (escalate 'too-long (list (cons 'message msg)
                                               (cons 'words wc)
                                               (cons 'max max-words))))
                    ((> grade max-grade)
                     (escalate 'too-complex (list (cons 'message msg)
                                                  (cons 'grade grade)
                                                  (cons 'max max-grade))))
                    (else msg)))))))
    
    (let ((validated (map validate-one messages)))
      (if (any? (lambda (x) (and (pair? x) (equal? (car x) 'escalate))) validated)
          (car (filter (lambda (x) (and (pair? x) (equal? (car x) 'escalate))) validated))
          validated)))
  
  ;; Pipeline: parse → transform → filter → template → validate.
  (let ((parsed (parse-csv csv-str)))
    (if (and (pair? parsed) (equal? (car parsed) 'escalate))
        parsed
        (let ((header (car parsed))
              (rows (cdr parsed)))
          (let ((transformed (transform-rows header rows)))
            (if (and (pair? transformed) (equal? (car transformed) 'escalate))
                transformed
                (let ((filtered (filter-by-years transformed min-years)))
                  (if (null? filtered)
                      (escalate 'no-matches min-years)
                      (let ((templated (template-rows filtered template-str)))
                        (if (and (pair? templated) (equal? (car templated) 'escalate))
                            templated
                            (validate-messages templated)))))))))))

(full-text-pipeline \"name,role,years\\nAlice,Engineer,5\\nBob,Designer,3\\nCarol,Manager,7\"
                    5
                    \"Congratulations, {{name}}! As a {{role}} with {{years}} years of experience, you qualify for our senior program.\"
                    15 50 12.0)
;; => (\"Congratulations, Alice! As a engineer with 5 years of experience, you qualify for our senior program.\"
;;     \"Congratulations, Carol! As a manager with 7 years of experience, you qualify for our senior program.\")
```

Bob is filtered out (only 3 years). Alice and Carol pass, their messages are templated, and both messages pass word count and readability validation. If Alice's message had been too long, we'd escalate with `(too-long ...)`. **ESCAPE** is multi-stage: we check at every boundary—parse, transform, filter (for emptiness), template, validate—and return the first failure.

This is the hardest program in the chapter: five stages, three text verbs, recursion, filtering, templating, and validation, all orchestrated into a single pipeline. It's the kind of program that a beginner could not write, but a master can compose cleanly from smaller pieces.

---

## Challenges

You've seen parsing, normalization, distance, slugification, templating, and multi-stage pipelines. Now write your own. Each challenge should be a **complete, standalone program** that runs top-to-bottom and produces a real result.

1. **Email Address Validator**: Write a program that takes a string and validates it as an email address (simple rules: one `@`, at least one character before and after, a `.` in the domain part). Use `text/normalize` to clean the input first, then parse character-by-character with recursion. Return `(valid . <email>)` or `(escalate invalid-email <reason>)`.

2. **Markdown Link Extractor**: Parse a Markdown string and extract all links in the format `[text](url)`. Return a list of `(text . url)` pairs. Handle malformed links by escalating if a `[` is not matched by `](...)`.

3. **Template with Defaults**: Extend the templating engine to support default values: `{{key|default}}`. If `key` is not in the alist, use `default` instead of escalating. Write a program that templates a string with this feature.

4. **CSV Column Projection**: Parse a CSV string, then project (select) only specified columns by name, reordering them as requested. Return a new CSV string with only those columns. Escalate if any requested column is missing.

5. **Text Diff Summary**: Given two strings, compute their Levenshtein distance, then generate a human-readable summary: `\"The texts differ by X edits (Y% similar).\"` Use `text/distance` and compute percentage similarity as `100 * (1 - distance / max-length)`.

6. **Multi-Template Report**: Given a list of data rows (as alists), a header template, a row template, and a footer template, generate a full report by templating the header once, each row once, and the footer once, then concatenating them with newlines. Validate that the final report is under a maximum character count, escalating if it exceeds.

---

You've reached the end of **Text & String Craft**. You've learned to parse ragged input, transform it recursively, template it cleanly, and validate it honestly—all while handling failure at every stage. These are the skills that let you take the messy strings the world hands you and turn them into structured data you can route through the rest of the runtime's programs. The next chapter will take these orchestration techniques even further, composing verbs across namespaces into routes that span the entire wired surface. Well done.
")
